<FIRST>r a AM-QuakeAftershock     04-09 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake Aftershock,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Aftershock Jars Northern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILPITAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake, an aftershock of a
larger quake last Monday, rattled windows but caused no reported
damage in Northern California on Sunday.
   The U.S. Geological Survey said the quake hit at 1:58 p.m.,
registering 3.4 on the Richter scale. The epicenter on the
Calaveras fault, seven miles east of Milpitas, was almost exactly
the same as Monday's quake measuring 4.9, the USGS said. Milpitas
is about 30 miles south of San Francisco.
   The open-ended Richter scale measures the energy released by an
earthquake by tabulating ground motion.
   Each increase of one number, as in a rise from 3.5 to 4.5, means
the ground motion is 10 times greater. A 3.5 earthquake can cause
slight damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
