<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalShootings     04-09 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Shootings,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage-Taker Kills Self; Cop Wounds Another By Mistake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A despondent man who said he had AIDS took up to
four people hostage at a hospital Saturday and then shot himself to
death. A short time later, one policeman accidentally shot another
while looking for the gunman.
   The wounded officer, identified as Jose Rodriguez, 32, was in
satisfactory condition after being hit in the shoulder by a bullet
fired by an officer who encountered him in a stairwell at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center.
   Police converged on the hospital about 1 a.m. after 39-year-old
Richard Carr of Manhattan entered the emergency room and demanded
to be readmitted, First Deputy Police Commissioner Richard Condon
said.
   Carr had discharged himself from the hospital on Friday against
the advice of doctors, who would not say why he had been in the
hospital, Condon said.
   The New York Daily News, in its Sunday editions, quoted a
witness who said she watched the beginning of the siege.
   Willie May Scott, a home health attendant, said she saw Carr
hand a note to a hospital guard after fidgeting for about 45
minutes in a waiting room with his girlfriend.
   ``Then he went into his pocket like this, real nice and easy,
took out the gun and put it to the man's head,'' Scott said. ``He
said, `I got AIDS. I don't have anything to lose. I'm going to die
anyway.' His girlfriend started screaming, `No! Don't do this!'''
   Carr had been a patient in the hospital for about two weeks,
said Anne Trachtenberg, a hospital spokeswoman. She wouldn't
identify his illness.
   When Carr returned early Saturday to the emergency room, he
``wanted to be readmitted and wanted the room he had originally,''
Condon said.
   With a .38-caliber revolver in hand, Carr took two security
guards, an X-ray technician and his girlfriend as hostages,
according to the commissioner.
   Trachtenberg, however, said Carr took only one security guard
hostage. The other three, she said, followed the pair to convince
the gunman ``to put down the gun and release the hostage.''
   Carr took the four people to a second-floor room in a
non-patient area, firing a shot into the door from the outside. He
then left the second floor and went down a stairway to the first
floor, Condon said.
   ``He opened a door, saw police, and shot himself,'' Condon said.
``Carr fired three shots. He shot himself in the chest twice and
then shot himself in the head.''
   Carr was declared dead at 2:46 a.m., Condon said.
   At some point apparently after Carr shot himself, Rodriguez was
shot in the shoulder by Officer Peter Heiberger, 26, according to
Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   ``The police officer made a mistake,'' Condon said of Heiberger.
He said the officer may have been confused by Rodriguez' dark
leather jacket, which is part of the police uniform but could have
made him look like a civilian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
