<FIRST>r a AM-Drive-byShootings     04-09 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drive-by Shootings,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Nine Injured in Drive-by Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drive-by barrage of 40 gunshots left two
people dead and nine injured Saturday in a neighborhood known for
gang activity, drug-dealing and violence.
   The victims, ranging in age from 14 to 20, had no known gang
affiliations, said Police Chief Frank Jordan during a news
conference at the Hall of Justice, where he was flanked by Mayor
Art Agnos.
   Both men appealed for public support in maintaining peace in the
Bayview-Hunters Point neighborhood and asked for information that
could help investigators looking for as many as four young male
suspects.
   Jordan identified the dead as 20-year-old Roshawn Johnson, who
was shot dead on the street, and 18-year-old Charles Hughes, who
died after being taken to Mission Emergency Hospital.
   Four victims were treated and released, but five remained in the
hospital late Saturday, including one man in serious but stable
condition, according to a nursing supervisor. Four others were in
satisfactory condition.
   The gunfire erupted about 12:45 a.m. Saturday. A gathering
involving about 200 people and sponsored by local church groups had
broken up about a mile away a short time earlier, police said.
   Three or four male youths had parked their car and were talking
to six girls when a four males drove by firing assorted weapons,
striking people, vehicles and buildings, said homicide inspector
Napoleon Hendrix.
   Authorities said the assailants appeared to have chosen their
male victims at random, and they believed the girls got caught in
the crossfire.
   ``They just said `Sunnydale' and they just opened up firing,''
said a young man who suffered a shotgun pellet wound to his right
wrist and told the San Francisco Examiner he was a member of the
Oakdale Mob gang.
   ``I told everybody to duck. I could see the bullets hitting all
around me. They be shooting girls and everything,'' he said.
   On March 23, police guarded over the funeral of Sunnydale gang
member Peter Lee, 19, fearing an outbreak of violence between
Sunnydale members and rivals.
   Police blame gangs for one homicide and 11 drive-by shootings so
far this year. Officials say gangs are fighting over the city's
lucrative cocaine trade. Jordan estimated there are 40 gangs in San
Francisco, with about 800 to 1,000 members.
</TEXT>
