<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 0031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolShooting     04-09 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Shooting,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Who Killed Assistant Principal Sentenced to Six Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy was sentenced to six
years in state prison for his role in a school cafeteria shooting
that killed an assistant principal.
   Jason McCoy embraced his mother Toni McCoy after his sentencing
Friday in the shootings at Pinellas Park High School. He had
pleaded guilty to third-degree murder and three counts of burglary
with a deadly weapon.
   ``Jason's a heck of a lot more prepared for it than I am,'' Mrs.
McCoy said. ``He just wants to get in, get it done and get out.''
   As part of a plea bargain, Circuit Judge Claire Luten ordered
McCoy placed in a youthful offender program for his role in the
Feb. 11, 1988, shooting that killed assistant principal Richard
Allen and injured two other school employees.
   With good behavior, McCoy could be released from prison in less
than two years.
   Co-defendant Jason Harless was sentenced last month to 17 years
in prison, followed by 20 years of probation.
   On the day of the shooting, McCoy ran away from home with
Harless, took two .38-caliber handguns from a neighbor's house and
went to say goodbye to friends at school.
   After learning the youths had guns, Allen and assistant
principal Nancy Blackwelder tackled McCoy. Student teacher Joseph
Bloznalis grabbed Harless, but he broke away after shooting
Bloznalis in the leg. Harless then shot Allen and Mrs. Blackwelder.
   Pinellas Park police tackled Harless outside the school, but
McCoy ran back to the house where the two had stolen the guns and
grabbed another one. He broke into his girlfriend's house and
surrendered after an hourlong police standoff.
</TEXT>
