<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Bombs     04-09 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Bombs,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Bombs Explode on Rail Lines in Navarrre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight bombs believed set by Basque
separatists exploded early Saturday along a railroad line in the
Navarre region, damaging rails and a power station but causing no
injuries, officials reported.
   Two hours before the pre-dawn blasts a man telephoned a local
travelers aid office and said the Basque separatist organization
ETA had placed several bombs on the rail line, according to the
regional governor's office said.
   It said six bombs exploded beside railroad power line posts at
Ciordia and two others damaged a transformer substation near Zuasti.
   Police demolition experts defused three other bombs at the
sites, the office said.
   The bombings were the first blamed on the ETA since the group
announced April 4 it would renew its 21-year-old campaign of
attacks to gain independence for the three-province Basque region
in northern Spain.
   Last week the ETA claimed the government of Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez had reneged on accords reached in peace talks that
began in January in Algeria.
   The government denied the allegation and said it was willing to
continue the talks if the ETA ruled out violence. ETA is an acronym
in the Basque language for homeland and liberty.
</TEXT>
