<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 0026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Trade     04-09 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Trade,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea To Expand Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea, in a move to ease
mounting U.S. pressure, announced a three-year plan Saturday to
open its market to 243 foreign agricultural and fishery products by
1991.
   Agriculture-Fishery Minister Kim Sik said South Korea will open
its market to 82 items this year, 76 more in 1990 and 85 more in
1991.
   Kim said the government will earmark $755 million to subsidize
or compensate farmers for any financial losses that may result from
foreign imports.
   ``The decision is final and we will not bow to any further U.S.
pressure to expand the plan,'' he said. ``Any further market
opening after 1991 will be decided at that time.''
   The 243 items covered under the plan include 62 of the 119
products Washington had said should be liberalized.
   Major items affected under the three-year plan include wheat,
soybean oil, alfafa, grapes, canned peaches, duck meat, fresh and
frozen salmon and peas.
   Tropical fruits _ including bananas, pineapples and kiwi fruits
_ will be free for import.
   The United States has threatened to retaliate unless South Korea
expands its restricted agricultural market wider to foreign
imports. Washington says America suffered an $8.6 billion trade
deficit with South Korea last year.
   Imports of 643 items of all 1,785 agricultural and fisheries
products classified under an internationally recognized agreement
are currently restricted by South Korea.
</TEXT>
