<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 0023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AfricaWatch     04-09 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa Watch,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Accuses Angolan Government, Rebels of Abuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The human rights monitor Africa Watch has
accused the Angolan government and U.S. backed rebels of abuses
ranging from indiscriminate use of land mines to restricting the
movement of civilians.
   In a report for release Sunday, ``Angola: Violations of the Laws
of War by Both Sides,'' Africa Watch, which is part of Human Rights
Watch, said civilians in the African country have borne the brunt
of the 14-year-old war between the government and UNITA, the
Portuguese acronym by which the South Africa-supported rebels are
known.
   ``Reportedly, Angola has the highest figures in the world for
civilian casualties of land mines ... estimates range from 20,000
to 50,000,'' Human Rights Watch staff member Jemera Rone wrote in
the 153-page report.
   The report accused both UNITA and the People's Republic of
Angola of indiscriminantly placing land mines in areas frequented
by civilians.
   Rone interviewed more than 80 Angolan refugees in Zaire and
Zambia at the end of 1988 to prepare the report. Africa Watch said
requests for visas to conduct research in Angola were ignored by
the Angolan government.
   The Angolan government was accused of forcibly displacing
thousands of civilians in a bid to deny support to UNITA, while
UNITA was accused of forcing civilians to fight or work on farms.
UNITA also has restricted the movements of civilians in areas under
its control, confiscating their food and forcing them into labor,
the report said.
   The government, according to the report, has attacked and killed
civilians in areas controlled by UNITA, and civilians in
government-controlled areas have been UNITA targets.
   Under a United Nations accord signed in December, Cuba was to
withdraw 50,000 troops sent to help the Angolan government battle
UNITA.
   South Africa agreed to end military aid to the Angolan rebels
and grant independence to Namibia, a southern African territory
neighboring Angola that South Africa had controlled since the
League of Nations gave it a mandate after World War I.
   In 1945, the United Nations told South Africa to relinquish
Namibia, but South Africa refused.
   Africa Watch said the U.N. accord left the United States as
UNITA's principal supporter.
   In a statement, Africa Watch said the United States ``has
consistently sought to minimize violations by UNITA.''

</TEXT>
