<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Oldest     04-09 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Oldest,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oldest Japanese Said to Turn 113</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman believed to be Japan's oldest person, Mitsu
Fujisawa, marked her 113th birthday Sunday in a hospital where she
has been under treatment since February, her daughter said.
   Her 71-year-old daughter, Midori Sato, said Mrs. Fujisawa is
``all right'' except for the neuralgia she is being treated for.
Neuralgia is severe pain associated with a nerve.
   She can walk unaided but has trouble hearing, her daughter said.
   Officials of Suwa Kyoritsu Hospital in Nagano, in north central
Japan, said nurses greeted Mrs. Fujisawa on her birthday, but there
was no special celebration.
   Such claims of longevity are often subject to dispute. The 1989
Guinness Book of World Records listed 112-year-old Birdie May Vogt
of Miami, Fla., as the oldest living person for whom there is
adequate authentication.
   Guinness says the greatest authenticated age any human ever
attained was 120 years in the case of Shigechiyo Izumi of Asan,
Japan. He died Feb. 21, 1986, after developing pneumonia.
</TEXT>
