<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Police With Rocks, Firebombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students battled riot police
with rocks and firebombs Sunday after police blocked protesters
trying to gain access to a university campus for an anti-government
rally.
   Several hundred students yelling ``Overthrow President Roh
Tae-woo!'' clashed with riot police outside the main gate of
Hanyang University in eastern Seoul.
   About 1,000 riot police ringed Hanyang for about four hours,
guarding roads around the school. All students were stopped for
identification and only those with Hanyang ID cards were allowed to
enter.
   Angry students tore down some of the brick wall around the
campus and dug up a cement roadway, using the debris to hurl at
police. Police retaliated with barrages of tear gas, causing shops
in the area to close and stopping traffic on the main street in
front of the campus.
   The rally was called to protest police action in putting down
labor unrest and the government's vow to arrest a leading
dissident, the Rev. Moon Il-kwan, when he returns to Seoul from
North Korea on Thursday.
   Moon made the unauthorized trip to talk with communist leaders
there about unification of the Korean peninsula, divided since 1945.
   The students also protested the action in which 14,000 riot
police stormed the Hyundai Heavy Industries shipyard in the port
city of Ulsan to end a three-month strike.
   Thousands of police remained in Ulsan, 150 miles southeast of
Seoul, to guard against further violence following the police
crackdown. Radical students and dissidents have been blocked from
getting near the shipyard, news reports said.
