<HEAD>Pope Canonizes 19th Century Italian Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday elevated to
sainthood a 19th century woman from Bologna who founded a religious
order dedicated to helping the sick and poor.
   Several thousand people attended the canonization ceremony in
St. Peter's Basilica for Clelia Barbieri, who died at the age of 23
in 1870.
   Ms. Barbieri founded the order Suore Minime dell'Addolorata,
which is based in Bologna and today counts followers in Italy,
India and Africa. She was beatified in 1968 by Pope Paul VI.
   During the ceremony, John Paul praised her work ``in times not
easy for the church'' and held her up as an example for today's
youth.
