<FIRST>r i AM-WaterfordCrystal     04-09 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waterford Crystal,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Waterford Chairman Resigns Over Reported Accounting Errors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the financially troubled
Waterford Glass Group PLC resigned Sunday after an audit showed
that accounting errors were made at the famed crystal and glass
manufacturer.
   Paddy Hayes, chairman and chief executive of the company that
owns Waterford Crystal in Ireland and Wedgewood China in Britain,
issued a statement in Dublin in which he disclosed that
``previously unreported figures'' had been found by accountants
Peat Marwick McLintock. He said he therefore resigned, ``in keeping
with well-established business tradition.''
   Hayes' resignation was announced hours after Dublin's Sunday
Tribune reported that the independent accountants' report will show
that inventories at three Waterford plants were overvalued by up to
$33 million.
   In his brief statement, Hayes did not elaborate on what he
described as accounting errors.
   Waterford hired Peat Marwick McLintock in January to conduct an
independent review of the group's financial performance and,
specifically, the valuation of its crystal inventory.
   In recent years, Waterford, one of Ireland's best known
manufacturers and one of the country's largest employers, has
suffered huge losses, mainly due to the weakening U.S. dollar.
One-third of the 3,000 employees in Waterford's crystal division
have lost their jobs.
   Half of Waterford's crystal is exported directly to the United
States, and another 35 percent is bought by Americans traveling
abroad.
   Hayes, former chief executive of Ford in Ireland, started
working for Waterford in 1985.
</TEXT>
