<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     04-09 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Chinese Commentary Doubts Vietnam's Withdrawal Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vietnam-Look Back, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's official news agency on Sunday expressed
doubts Vietnam will pull all its troops out of Cambodia by the end
of September as promised, saying Hanoi has ``a notorious record of
insincerity.''
   The Xinhua News Agency in its commentary said Vietnam is trying
to conceal a large number of troops in Cambodia by moving them into
the ranks of the Hanoi-backed Hun Sen faction or turning them into
armed immigrants.
   Xinhua said there was ``nothing new'' in Vietnam's statement
last week that it will leave Cambodia by September, and it said
seven partial pullouts announced between 1982 and 1988 ``were a
sham.''
   ``Hanoi has had a notorious record of insincerity in terms of
the troop withdrawal,'' it said.
   Previously, Vietnam had said it would only withdraw all its
troops by September if a political settlement of the Cambodian
conflict had been reached.
   China supports the anti-Vietnamese resistance in Cambodia and
has long demanded that Soviet-backed Vietnam end its 10-year
military presence in Cambodia. Hanoi has withdrawn about half its
troops and says 50,000 remain. Western analysts put the number at
70,000.
   ``If it is really implementing its promise of a total troop
pullout, Vietnam should withdraw not only all of its troops of
aggression, who wear uniforms and carry weapons, but also those
concealing their identity among the Phnom Penh puppet troops or as
immigrants,'' the news agency said.
   The commentary said Vietnam's refusal to accept U.N. monitoring
``shows that Hanoi is not willing to receive real and effectual
international supervision.''
   In what appeared to be new optimism in peace talks, Cambodian
resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk on Sunday extended his
plans for a meeting next month with Cambodia's prime minister,
saying it will take ``at least two days.''
   Both sides initially spoke only of meeting May 2 in Jakarta,
Indonesia. But in a message to his son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh,
in Bangkok, Thailand, Sihanouk said, ``My unofficial talks with Mr.
Hun Sen about Cambodia will take at least two days. I will return
to Bangkok (from Jakarta) on May 4 or 5.''
   Vietnamese troops entered Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted
the communist Khmer Rouge.
   In an interview later Sunday with the British Broadcasting
Corp., Sihanouk said he believed a ``good settlement'' could be
reached by August if his proposal for an international conference
on Cambodia were carried out in early summer.
</TEXT>
