<DOCNO> AP890409-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Figueres     04-09 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Figueres,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Costa Rican President Gravely Ill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jose Figueres, whom
many consider the father of Costa Rican democracy, remained
hospitalized in serious condition on Sunday, his doctor said.
   ``Although he has improved slightly, he is still not out of
danger and we are treating a kidney infection,'' said Dr. Jaime
Gutierrez.
   Gutierrez said Figueres, 83, was admitted Friday night to San
Juan de Dios Hospital after suffering severe chest pains and kidney
problems.
   The doctor said Saturday that Figueres was too old to be fitted
with a pacemaker and that he was in danger of dying. The Rev.
Alberto Casals, a Roman Catholic priest, told reporters he had
delivered last rites to Figueres.
   Five of Figueres' six children and his two former wives were at
the hospital along with some government officials, hospital sources
reported.
   An adviser to President Oscar Arias said the president may cut
short a trip to Canada if Figueres' condition does not improve.
   Arias recently said Figueres is ``like my second father and has
been my political guide.'' Both belong to the governing National
Liberation Party, which Figueres founded in 1953.
   In 1948, after elections many considered fraudulent, Figueres
led a band of rebels in a brief but bloody revolution that
overthrew President Fernando Calderon Guardia who had allied
himself with the Communist Party.
   Figueres took over as president of a provisional junta for a
year, banning the communists and overseeing the writing of a new
constitution that provided increased social services.
   He also abolished the armed forces, making Costa Rica the only
nation in Latin America _ and one of the few in the world _ without
a military. Since then, Costa Rica has been Central America's most
enduring democracy.
   Figueres served a second presidential term from 1953 to 1958 and
a third from 1970 to 1974.
</TEXT>
