<HEAD>Beleaguered Judge Blames Politics for Troubles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who said he lightened the sentence
of a murderer because his two homosexual victims were ``asking for
trouble'' is claiming that demands for his dismissal are
politically motivated.
   The state Supreme Court and the Commission on Judicial Conduct
have launched inquiries into the behavior of district Judge Jack
Hampton, who made the comment in an interview with the Dallas Times
Herald in December that touched off widespread criticism.
   In documents filed Friday with the Supreme Court, Hampton said a
petition from 17 lawyers demanding his dismissal ``is politically
motivated without basis or foundation.''
   Hampton said in the interview that one reason he sentenced the
man convicted of killing the two men to 30 years instead of life in
prison was that the victims were ``queers cruising the streets for
teen-age boys'' who were ``asking for trouble.''
   Court records show the defendant's testimony was the only
evidence that the two men were soliciting sex.
   Gay and civil rights groups have organized demonstrations, some
urging the removal of the judge.
   Hampton, a Republican who has been on the bench for almost eight
years, denied that his behavior during or after the trial could be
construed as biased and said the Democrats were out to get him.
   The attacks are ``the reflection of a county and a courthouse
charged with political activity in which one political party
undertakes to bash the other political party,'' he said.
