<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-LAMayor     04-09 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Mayor,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Tom Bradley Seeks Fifth Term at Age 71</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Khushro Ghandhi is cq in penultimate graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's second-largest city votes for a
mayor on Tuesday, and despite increased crime, pollution and
traffic, Tom Bradley appears headed toward an unprecedented fifth
term.
   The city's first black mayor, a former policeman and son of a
sharecropper, is 71, yet energetic as ever. During his 16 years in
office, proud residents says the city has grown into a cultural
center, a world-class Pacific Rim metropolis and an ethnically rich
mecca for opportunity-seeking immigrants.
   But with the city's explosive growth has come traffic and
building congestion, pollution, sewage problems, rampant drug
trafficking and uncontrollable street gangs who committed more than
250 murders in the city last year.
   As Los Angeles continues to swell beyond its 3 million citizens
who speak more than 70 languages, the main question in Tuesday's
mayoral election is who will lead it into the 1990s and 21st
century.
   Bradley says he can and he will.
   ``I've done an excellent job over the last 16 years. We have
many programs that are under way or planned, and I want to follow
through on them,'' he said Thursday.
   ``The years ahead,'' Bradley continued, ``can be and should be
and must be the years of air and water made clean, of neighborhoods
made safer, of growth and progress that weighs human as well as
material values.''
   The mayor's opponents disagree. They include a city councilman,
former television commentator, an aerospace worker, and a woman who
dances around the Civic Center in a green dress.
   Despite the opposition, though, few expect that Bradley will
even need a runoff in order to win another four-year term. A runoff
would be scheduled for June 6 only if no one gets more than 50
percent of the vote Tuesday.
   Bradley's main challenger is a freshman city councilman, Nate
Holden, 59, who only recently gained widespread attention by buying
back Uzis and AK-47 rifles from citizens and destroying them.
   Holden says Bradley has been in office too long and predicts
that residents ``are not going to vote for him out of habit
anymore.''
   In the final weeks of campaigning, Holden and other blacks have
also accused Bradley of ignoring his roots and the impoverished
south side in favor of courting big business and foreign trade.
   The stress on foreign trade also bothers candidate Baxter Ward,
a former TV news commentator and former county supervisor, who says
Bradley spend so much time away from the city he ``thinks City Hall
is in Tokyo, Japan.''
   In perhaps the most damaging personal issue, Bradley is under
investigation by the city attorney's office for performing
consulting work with two banks that do business with the city.
Bradley has returned the $18,000 in fees he was paid and called the
charges politically motivated.
   Bradley has been dubbed the ``Teflon mayor,'' with polls
indicating residents do not blame him for the city's woes.
   In a recent Los Angeles Times poll, 65 percent surveyed said
their quality of life worsened during the Bradley years to the
point that half have recently considered moving.
   However, in another Times poll, 78 percent of Hispanics, 70
percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a favorable
impression of the Democratic mayor.
   ``They are not holding him accountable for it. The drugs and the
gangs are causing it. But they don't think Tom Bradley is causing
it. He's a lucky politician,'' said Joe Cerrell, a political
consultant who has known Bradley since he was a police lieutenant
in the 1950s.
   Arnold Steinberg, a pollster who assessed the race for a liberal
councilman who decided not to challenge Bradley, said they
concluded Bradley's popularity was insurmountable.
   ``Tom Bradley is too likable,'' Cerrell agreed. ``He's a nice
guy. It shows he has a rare quality. He doesn't scare people.''
   The other mayoral hopefuls are socialist Joel Britton, an oil
refinery worker; singer-dancer Eileen Anderson; teachers Raul Reyes
and Maria Elizabeth Munoz; consultant Khushro Ghandhi; aerospace
worker Stewart Alexander; politician Leonard Earl Miropol; and
political scientist Gary Passi.
   The city's 1.4 million voters also will choose eight of the city
council's 15 seats, a city attorney, a controller and school board
members.
</TEXT>
