<FIRST>r a AM-VolunteersWeek     04-09 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Volunteers Week,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelter for Young People Relies on Efforts of Volunteers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHEILA NORMAN-CULP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everyone at Covenant House, a shelter for young
people just off Times Square, seems to have a different idea of
what motivates the 350 people who volunteer some of their time
there each week.
   ``You should volunteer because you'll learn a lot about
generosity, humility, giving of yourself,'' says the Rev. Bruce
Ritter, the shelter's founder.
   ``Voluntarism has become more necessary,'' says Arlene
Stepputat, director of volunteers. ``It was an answer to all the
cutbacks in social services.''
   The federal government has encouraged such an answer, which is
why this is National Volunteer Week. The Covenant House Volunteer
Department is among 18 recipients of a President's Volunteer Action
Award, which Ritter, Ms. Stepputat and Andrew Boone, a
representative of the agency's volunteers, are scheduled to receive
Monday night at the White House.
   ``I volunteered after having asked myself for the hundredth time
what could I do,'' said Kristin King, who has been a volunteer for
more than a year. ``I was tired of walking by homeless people on
the street. I decided not to be helpless anymore.''
   ``I do it more for myself now than for the kids,'' said Kevin
Callahan, who works at Covenant House every Monday night. ``Of
course, they benefit, too. You know that you're needed, especially
after you serve dinner for a couple of hundred kids.''
   There are volunteers at all Covenant House programs, including
those in Anchorage, Alaska; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Houston; Los
Angeles; and New Orleans; and in Canada, Mexico, Guatemala,
Honduras and Panama.
   The agency said that in 1988, the New York program served more
than 12,700 youths, some of whom returned more than once for help.
The nationwide crisis hotline for youths and their families
(1-800-999-9999) took a million calls, the agency said.
   After taking training, volunteers at Covenant House staff the
computer room, the library and the gym. They serve meals, sort
clothes, interview new residents, escort youngsters to hospitals.
They ride the Outreach van, which goes into the city's seedy
districts to try to get homeless youngsters off the streets.
   Volunteers also work on the New York shelter's Special Needs
Floor, which serves youngsters with AIDS and related diseases.
   It's not easy to be a volunteer.
   ``The hardest part is saying no to the kids, even when you know
you have to,'' says Ann Turnbull, who began volunteering in
February. ```No, you can't have another juice, no, you can't take
three pairs of socks, no, no, no.
   ``You've talked with these kids, and you've gotten some idea of
how terrible their lives are and you want to load them up with
juice and socks.''
   ``The hardest thing is seeing the kids who won't make it,'' said
Chris Foote, who has volunteered for more than a year.
   ``You just have to keep coming here, giving as much as you can.
Any job you do here involves love _ it doesn't matter what you do.''
   Most of the part-time volunteers arrive at night, after work,
and are between the ages of 25 to 40, said Ms. Stepputat. About 90
percent of them hold full-time jobs. There are also retirees.
   Full-time volunteers include the Covenant House board and those
in the Faith Community, nicknamed Ritter's ``peace corps,'' who
donate about a year each to work with street kids.
   Even if Covenant House had money for more staff counselors, Ms.
Stepputat said it would still rely heavily on volunteers because
they ``bring a specialness that money cannot buy.'' she said. ``It
just can't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
