<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEBOYGAN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cash would have come in handy in the
1960s, when he adopted nine orphans and had five of his own
children, but a former reporter says he'll retire for good after
winning $6 million in the Michigan lottery.
   Chuck Fisher, 62, of Lansing, Mich., said Friday he plans to
leave his job as assistant to the director of the Michigan
Department of Transportation and settle down with his winnings.
   In the early 1960s, he and his wife, Kerry, adopted nine
Sheboygan children whose father had died falling from a ladder.
   Fisher, then a reporter for The Sheboygan Press, knew the
children from having covered the story of their mother's death of
leukemia five years earlier.
   He said he bought his winning ticket at a variety story in a
Lansing mall and had the numbers selected for him at random by a
Michigan lottery computer.
   At a press conference Friday, he received the first of 19 annual
$300,000 checks. After withholding taxes, Fisher netted $240,000 on
the first check.
   The Fishers' children, ranging in age from 27 to 39, live in
various parts of the country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ostrich plumes, glitter and music returned
to South Philadelphia as 23 string bands staged a springtime strut
to make up for having shirked the New Year's Day parade.
   Many of the bands were booed by crowds on Jan. 1, when they took
buses to the reviewing stands of the traditional Mummer's Parade to
avoid damage to their elaborate costumes from rain and snow.
   Saturday was a different story, although the crowds were smaller
than for the earlier parade.
   Saxophones, banjos, drums, xylophones, violins, cellos and
accordians provided accompaniment to the antics of feather-clad
strutters.
   Duffy String Band's costumes had a patriotic red, white and blue
motif to go with their theme, ``Of Thee I Swing.'' Greater Bucks
County String Band dressed for a ``Beach Party'' with tropical
attire and costumes shaped like ocean waves.
   But diehard Mummers fans said it just wasn't right to have such
a parade so late in the year.
