<HEAD>GOP for Choice and Other Notes From the Pro-Abortion Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Grundmann of Kokomo, Ind., is proud of
her Republican credentials. ``I voted for Dan Quayle,'' she boasts.
   But when it comes to abortion, she parts company with the GOP.
So, she joined about 1,000 other Indiana residents in marching in
Sunday's abortion rights march.
   ``I'll be 53 years old this year, and I never dreamed of
marching in anything,'' she said.
   Why, then, did she march Sunday?
   ``I wanted the rest of the United States to know many
Republicans are pro-choice,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For Dolly Krone, abortion was too important an issue to ignore.
   The 74-year-old Krone was one of about 30 people who traveled
thousands of miles from Anchorage, Alaska, to participate in
Sunday's rally for abortion rights.
   ``If we could make a difference at all, we wanted to ... It just
make a difference,'' she said. ``The citizens should be listened
to.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Students from Wellesley College in Massachusetts claimed that
one-quarter of the private women's college were at the rally.
   That's 10 busloads.
   Sue Anne Bruromphongsa, a freshman from Rockford, Ill., said:
``I thought we were safe but when George Bush was elected, I knew
we were in trouble.''
   The National Organization for Women said students from at least
458 campuses in 40 states had traveled to Washington to participate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Nobody likes the idea of an abortion,'' said actor Leonard
Nimoy, one of dozens of celebrities who traveled to Washington for
the rally.
   ``But if it has to happen,'' he said, ``there should be freedom
of choice.''
   Nimoy, remembered as the Mr. Spock of ``Star Trek'' fame,
sported an ``Honorary Sister'' pin on his white sweatshirt.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The differences aired during the rally Sunday were not limited
to the subject of abortion.
   Law enforcement authorities and rally organizers offered grossly
divergent crowd estimates. U.S. Park Police, working in conjunction
with the Capitol and Metro Police Departments, put the crowd at
300,000.
   Eleanor Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority,
said it was double that. ``They always low-ball our numbers,'' she
said of the police estimate.
   ``This is no ordinary march,'' Smeal said. ``We took over the
city.''
</TEXT>
