<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Refusenik     04-09 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Refusenik,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refusenik Arrives In Britain For Medical Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish refusenik Georgy Samoilovich, who sought
permission to leave the Soviet Union for 10 years, arrived in
London on Sunday for medical treatment.
   ``I am very happy to be here. It is a miracle,'' said
Samoilovich, a 66-year-old physicist who suffers from throat cancer.
   ``It is a victory of my friends and a lot of people who have
struggled for my freedom in England, the U.S.A. and throughout the
world,'' he said as he was greeted at Heathrow Airport by
supporters.
   Samoilovich had been on a list of emigration cases British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher planned to raise with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev on his visit to Britain last week. The Soviet
Union announced on the eve of Gorbachev's visit that Samoilovich
was free to leave.
   Samoilovich, of Moscow, first applied to emigrate in 1979. He
was fired from a defense-related job and the Soviets refused
repeated applications on the grounds he was involved in secret work.
   He will be treated for throat lymphoma at London's Royal Marsden
cancer hospital.
</TEXT>
