<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Laws 1stLd-Writethru   04-09 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Laws, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0673,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweeping Decree Imposes Fines, Jail Sentences to Control Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS background at end on articles 70 and 190.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With AM-Soviet-Georgia, Bjt
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has passed strict new laws aimed at
quelling ethnic unrest and burgeoning calls for change in the
Soviet system, including mandating prison terms and fines for
anyone who publicly insults a government body.
   The Tass news agency said the decree was approved Saturday at a
meeting of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet.
   That was a day after Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
returned from London to more ethnic unrest, this time in the
southern republic of Georgia. Sixteen people were killed early
Sunday when soldiers dispersed thousands of protesters in the
city's center.
   As president, Gorbachev is chairman of the Presidium. The move
by the collective presidency signaled the Kremlin's determination
to crack down on unrest, even at the cost of an improved human
rights image.
   Tass said the decree prohibits ``public appeals for undermining
and overthrowing the Soviet state and social system, as well as the
publication or circulation of materials containing such ideas.''
   Such actions can be punished by three years in jail and a fine
of up to $3,200 _ almost an entire year's salary for an average
Soviet worker. Carried out repeatedly, or by an organized group,
the same actions are punishable by a prison term of up to seven
years.
   The decree imposes prison terms of up to three years and fines
of up to $3,200 for ``public insults or the discrediting of the
U.S.S.R. supreme bodies of state power and government,'' as well as
government and public organizations formed by it.
   Tass said the decree also prohibits appeals to kindling ethnic
tensions and racial hostility and appeals to commit treason.
   It could not be determined how Soviet authorities would use
their new powers, but the language was broad enough that it could
be used against protesters like those in Georgia, who were
demanding independence from the Soviet Union, as well as more
moderate grassroots political organizations in the Baltic republics.
   Sergei Petrov, a Soviet who long has been refused permission by
authorities to emigrate to the United States, charged that the
decree ``crosses out all they promised'' at the recently completed
Vienna conference on security and cooperation in Europe.
   Petrov said he regarded the new decree, as outlined by Tass, as
worse than existing laws, which require that the defendant
knowingly was spreading lies.
   Two Soviet laws now prohibit anti-Soviet agitation and
propaganda and anti-Soviet slander, and they were used for years to
imprison dissidents and Jewish refuseniks.
   Article 70 of the criminal code prohibits ``agitation or
propaganda carried on for the purpose of subverting or weakening
Soviet authority'' and ``circulating ... slanderous fabrications
which defame the Soviet state and social system.''
   Article 190 is aimed particularly at limiting spoken ``slander''
against the Soviet system.
   In October, Justice Minister Boris Kravtsov told the Tass news
agency that Article 190 would be eliminated and Article 70 would be
substantially rewritten under a series of legal reforms.
</TEXT>
