<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Education     04-09 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Education,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Acknowledge They Have Few Alternatives to Bush Education
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress was generally critical of the $441
million education package offered last week by President Bush, but
many members and their staffs acknowledged they have few
alternatives to the president's initiatives.
   Instead, most argue that scarce funds should be used to
strengthen successful existing programs which have already been
authorized and they say they'll use the budget appropriations and
authorization process to make their point.
   ``We don't have anything that would be an alternative to Bush's
program,'' said one House Education and Labor Committee staffer.
   He said the panel might make changes in the school improvement
act passed last year to incorporate some of the Bush proposal ``but
they would not be offering anything totally new this session.''
   ``We want to see the current law implemented,'' echoed committee
Chairman Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif.
   ``There's no need fooling around with new programs when you're
not implementing the current ones,'' he said.
   ``Why take money out of successful programs if money is
limited?'' queried Hawkins.
   The Education Excellence Act proposed by Bush would include:
   _a $250 million grant program to reward schools that have cut
drug use or dropout rates, raised standard test scores or improved
in other ways,
   _$100 million on a new magnet schools program,
   _and $7.6 million for grants to outstanding teachers.
   Other parts of the bill would develop new ways to certify
teachers, help urban schools and enlarge the endowments of
historically black colleges.
   Some lawmakers praised the president's efforts to reward
educational excellence, but said current programs that serve a
greater number of students and teachers should be expanded.
   Republican Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey said the Pell grants
and student loan programs which help defray college tuition costs
are highest on her list of priority programs because she said they
are important to the nation's competitive future.
   ``I'd like to see those existing programs fully funded,'' said
Roukema.
   ``We can't continue to add to these programs and not understand
the tax and budget consequences,'' she added.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, from whom the grant program got its name,
emphasized that Bush had not clarified whether the new programs
would be funded with new money or from cuts to existing programs.
   ``This is of equal concern to me,'' said the Rhode Island
Democrat.
   However, Pell said he was disappointed that Bush's package
``does not contain specific proposals to strengthen critically
important programs already in existence'' _ programs such as
Chapter 1 for low-achieving children, compensatory education for
disadvantaged children and Pell grants.
   ``These programs form the foundation of the federal commitment
to provide educational opportunity and access for students in
need,'' Pell said.
   Many, like Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., recognize the
president's proposal as ``only a first step.'' But he said Bush
would have to take greater steps than the less than 2 percent
spending boost he has proposed because ``that's only half of what
it would take to keep up with inflation.''
   However, Roukema zeroed in on the likely costs for the
president's program and any competing ideas. ``Since they have to
be authorized, one could debate at the authorization level, but the
real fight, I guess, will come in appropriations.''
   At any rate, Congress is likely ``to make its case at each point
along the way,'' said Roukema.
</TEXT>
