<FIRST>r a AM-KentuckyLottery     04-09 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kentucky Lottery,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentuckians Going Wild Over New Lottery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentuckians have gone wild over their new
lottery, and horse racing officials are worried that the
state-sponsored games will cut into the money laid down at the
state's venerable racetracks.
   From the opening of the lottery Tuesday through Saturday
evening, $20 million worth of scratch-off tickets were sold, and
the first week of sales should top $25 million, said Frank O.
Keener, president of the Kentucky Lottery Corp., the private group
that operates the games.
   If they hit $30 million, it would set a state per-capita sales
record now held by Florida, which had $8 worth of sales for each
citizen when the lottery began there last year, he said.
   Lottery tickets were a hot item in Salyersville, in economically
depressed eastern Kentucky.
   ``About once a year the carnival comes to town, and it takes all
the loose change out of here,'' said Mayor Joe Howard. ``Now the
lottery's here, and it'll take out money all year around.''
   At Lexington's Keeneland Race Course, where a 16-day meet began
Friday, the first-day handle was down almost $1 million from last
year's opening, although officials said the downturn could in part
be due to unseasonably cold weather.
   ``There are just so many leisure dollars out there,'' said
William Greely, Keeneland president. He said the lottery would
represent ``one more slice of the pie.''
   But some racing officials think the lottery, however popular at
the moment, has little chance of eroding Kentucky's deep-rooted
interest in racing.
   ``The lottery is primarily a game of chance, and thoroughbred
horse racing and harness horse racing involve a skilled decision on
your part based on many factors,'' said Lyle Robey, chairman of the
Kentucky State Racing Commission.
   ``The lottery may be fashionable now. I don't ever see it taking
over thoroughbred gambling interests.''
   Experience from other states shows that lottery sales usually
slow after the first week, said Larry Sipes, executive vice
president of the Kentucky Lottery Corp.
   The state had garnered about $7.1 million in lottery income by
Saturday. There were at least 26 $5,000 winners in the
``DreamStakes'' game, and 380 people had won $1,000, the grand
prize in ``Beginner's Luck.'' The DreamStakes winners get to enter
in another drawing tied to next month's Kentucky Derby.
   Connie Phan, manager of a Lexington Convenient Food Mart, said
food and other sales had dropped by $200 or $300 a day.
   ``This area, the money is very limited for them,'' said Mrs.
Phan, whose store is located near a low-income section of the city.
``Lots of people are on welfare and food stamps.''
   ``A lot of them will come in and pick some of them up in the
morning, they'll come back at lunch, and then they come back after
work,'' said Steve Finley, assistant manager at a Louisville
convenience store.
   ``It's been wild, it really has,'' said Beverly Allen, assistant
manager of a Gulf service station. One man spent three hours at the
counter scratching off $100 in tickets, then went home and came
back with more money, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
