<FIRST>r a AM-RedRiverFlooding     04-09 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red River Flooding,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Weather Causes Red River To Crest Early</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORHEAD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold weather slowed the rise of the Red
River on Sunday, giving a reprieve to weary homeowners who have
fought flooding with pumps, dikes and heaps of sandbags.
   The river, which forms the boundary between Minnesota and North
Dakota, was expected to crest Sunday evening a foot lower than had
been anticipated.
   ``The river seems to be slowing down, and that's good news,''
Col. Roger Baldwin of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers said during
a tour of the flood-ravaged area with Gov. Rudy Perpich. The
governor later said he would ask for federal disaster relief.
   The bloated river flooded Breckenridge and Wahpeton, N.D.,
across the river last week, damaging as many as 900 homes and
forcing the evacuation of scores of people.
   Lou Bennett, chief meterologist for the National Weather
Service, said cold weather Saturday night in Moorhead and Fargo,
N.D., helped slow the runoff from the winter's plentiful snowfall.
   Temperatures fell into the teens Saturday night and stayed well
below freezing Sunday. Daytime highs usually are in the 40s during
this time of the year.
   The weather service changed its crest prediction to 35{ feet for
the two communities. Forecasters had been expecting a 36{-foot
crest on Monday.
   Bennett said cold weather should cause the water to drain away
more slowly. The river was expected to remain above its 17-foot
flood stage at Fargo for at least 10 days, he said.
   Residents of Fargo and Moorhead had ample time to prepare for
the flood. Hundreds of homeowners built sandbag dikes around their
property to keep out encroaching water.
</TEXT>
