<FIRST>r a AM-ConfederateDaughters     04-09 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Confederate Daughters,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confederate Home Residents, Daughters Of Soldiers, To Be Moved From
Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decades ago, daughters of Civil War
soldiers were promised they would be looked after for life in the
stately Confederate Home for Women, but the eight women still
living in the landmark are being moved to make more room for a
museum, officials said.
   The women, age 84 to 98, surrendered their worldly possessions
and future inheritance in exchange for the promise of lifetime care
in the two-story building nestled among the magnolias behind the
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts.
   Once the women are moved, the museum will take the building for
its own use, and the antiques filling the home will be sold.
   ``The museum wants our home,'' said Faye Oliff, a member of the
home's board of governors who opposed the move. ``They want it so
bad. They've been like damn vultures waiting for the ladies to die
so they can get it.''
   The Confederate Home for Women is located near historic Monument
Avenue, lined with statues of rebel generals celebrating the days
when Richmond was the capital of the Confederacy. Dozens of
daughters of Confederate soldiers have lived in the home since the
1930s.
   But after more than a year of negotiations among key
legislators, museum officials and the home's board of directors, a
decision has been reached to turn the home over to the museum, and
send the women to a modern place 20 miles out of town, The
Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger Star of Norfolk reported Sunday.
   The women themselves won't find out about the move until later
this week, officials said. They will lose dozens of worn but
valuable antiques in use in the home, some they or previous
residents brought threre, others bequeathed by wealthy Southerners.
   The antiques will be sold off, with board members receiving
first dibs at prices based on a 9-year-old appraisal, the newspaper
reported.
   ``Something needs to be done to stop (the private sale),'' Ms.
Oliff said. ``I think it all ought to be sold at public auction to
ensure the home gets a fair price for it.''
   Ms. Oliff said she tried unsuccessfully to persuade other board
members to open the home to paying descendants of Confederate
soldiers. The board also denied her proposal that a smaller home
for the women be opened about eight blocks away.
   The antiques included a 1770 Chippendale American-made mahogany
grandfather clock, valued at $5,000 according to a recent appraisal
by R.E. Crawford and Associates of Richmond. The clock was
appraised for about one-fifth that much in 1980, said Holly C.
DeJarnette, the home's administrator.
   Museum officials and legislators denied they had pressured the
home to close, and said board members first suggested it.
   ``They came to us,'' said Hunter Andrews, Democratic chairman of
the state Senate Finance Committee.
</TEXT>
