<FIRST>r a AM-Mailman'sMilestone     04-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mailman's Milestone,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longest Serving Postal Worker Turns 80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAYMOND, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calvin Coolidge was president and letters
took 2-cent stamps when postman August Sutter started his rounds on
the backroads of central Illinois.
   Sixty years, 11 presidents and 13 postal rate increases later
he's still at it, the longest-serving postal employee in the
country.
   ``I was very fortunate to have a job during the Depression,''
Sutter said.
   When he started his route in 1929, Sutter motored a Model-T Ford
over the 31 miles of country roads. During the spring he used a
horse to deliver the mail because the dirt roads turned to mud and
were impassable by car.
   Now he drives a white Oldsmobile Cutlass more than 80 miles each
day to about 139 postal patrons _ including three of his original
customers.
   ``You're out there where there's no pressure, you're out there
with nature and you see things, watch things grow, talk to
people,'' he said.
   On Saturday, the U.S. Postal Service organized a party at the
Raymond Post Office to celebrate Sutter's 80th birthday.
   Coffee and sweets were laid out for the affair, including a
2-foot red, white and blue cake decorated with the postal service's
eagle emblem.
   ``I thanked my patrons for putting up with me for 60 years,
because you make a few errors in your life _ you know,
miss-throws,'' Sutter said, using the postal carriers' jargon for
delivering mail to the wrong person's box.
   Sutter, who will be honored in Washington next month, has served
longer than any of the other 800,000 postal service employees, said
George Skinner, a spokesman for the service in suburban Chicago.
   The biggest change between 1929 and now, Sutter said, is
blacktop. In the early years the length of his working day depended
on what the rain, sleet and snow were doing to the roadway.
   Sutter started out at $2,010 a year, with a 5-cents-a-mile
equipment allowance. His salary has risen to about $23,000, the
allowance to 31{ cents.
   Sutter says he has no plans to retire at least until January,
when he completes another year on the job.
   ``If the health's good, I may continue,'' he said.
</TEXT>
