<DOCNO> AP890409-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1758EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JailEscapees     04-09 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Escapees,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailbreaks Leave 12 Inmates at Large in Massachusetts, Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Dedham, Mass., dated story listed in AM-News Advisory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Massachusetts and Pennsylvania searched Sunday for
eleven escaped prisoners who remained at large following unrelated
jailbreaks.
   Officials in both states blamed the escapes on overcrowding and
understaffing in outdated jails.
   Thirteen prisoners slipped away from the 173-year-old Norfolk
County House of Corrections in Dedham, Mass., after sawing through
a prison window bar Friday night. Two were recaptured shortly after
the break and five more were arrested in a massive manhunt Saturday.
   In New Castle, Penn., seven prisoners, including a convicted
rapist, escaped the Lawrence County Jail on Saturday evening by
cutting a hole in the metal ceiling of their cell. One was captured
about an hour later and a second turned himself Sunday afternoon.
   The Pennsylvania escape came just days after the New Castle News
ran a lengthy series of articles that described overcrowding at the
jail. Built in 1964 to house 43 minor offenders, the Lawrence
County Jail has been holding nearly three times that number
recently, including several prisoners charged with murder.
   ``It goes back to the same old cliche _ overpopulated and
understaffed,'' deputy warden Anthony Pagley said.
   In Massachusetts, Norfolk County Sheriff Clifford Marshall
offered a similar description of the problems at his jail, the
oldest section of which was built in 1816.
   ``There is no way with 170 people in here we can watch every
facet of the institution,'' Marshall said. ``I would like to think
that we can, but we can't.''
   Actually, although the jail is under a federal cap of 172
inmates, it held 246 inmates on Friday night. Marshall said the
cells have rusted bars that can be cut through easily. A contract
was signed last October to build a new county jail.
   Residents of Dedham, an affluent Boston suburb, responded to the
escape with both anger and resignation.
   ``How can they let 13 guys escape over a wall?'' said Katherine
Leary. ``It's kind of amazing.''
   After cutting through inch-thick window bars, the inmates
crossed a roof and scaled a 15-foot brick wall topped with razor
wire to escape, authorities said.
   Of the six men who were being sought Sunday, two were serving
prison terms of less than a year, one for breaking and entering,
the other for driving to endanger. Four were in jail pending trial,
three for breaking and entering, the fourth for driving to
endanger. They ranged in age from 18 to 37.
   Marshall said someone outside the prison probably tossed
hacksaws over the wall. ``They can cut through these old bars in a
matter of minutes,'' he said. ``And they try it all the time.''
   In New Castle, a town of about 34,000 people 40 miles northwest
of Pittsburgh, the escapees also used a hacksaw blade to cut
through the metal ceiling of their cell, Pagley said. He said
officials do not know where the men got the blade.
   In addition to the one rapist, those at large included three men
awaiting trial for burglary and one for robbery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
