<DOCNO> AP890409-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-09 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Pakistan Escalating War In Border Regions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib's government on Sunday
accused Pakistan of escalating Moslem guerrilla attacks in border
regions and said more than 270 people, mostly guerrillas, were
killed over the weekend.
   Heavy rocket and artillery attacks were launched on the eastern
towns of Khost and Ghazni in the past 24 hours while the battle for
the key eastern city of Jalalabad continued, the government said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani told a Kabul news
conference that government troops killed 195 opposition fighters
and wounded 142 in the Jalalabad area. He did not give any
casualties for the government side.
   He also said 54 more fighters were killed by government fire
near Sarobi, which is midway between Jalalabad and Kabul on the
only paved road linking the two cities.
   There was no way to confirm the casualty figures.
   ``If Pakistan continues this kind of unbridled involvement in
the military destructive activities of the extremists against
Afghanistan, it is bearing the responsibility of the grave
consequences,'' Amani said.
   In response to a question, Amani said Afghanistan was not
threatening to declare war.
   In New York, U.N. officials speaking anonymously said Afghan
Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil was scheduled to meet
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Monday. Wakil, who
arrived Saturday, has asked for an emergency meeting of the
Security Council.
   On Friday, a long-range Soviet-made Scud-B missile was fired
from Kabul toward Jalalabad and landed across the border in
Pakistan. The Kabul government said it was an accident. Pakistan
said no one was hurt but protested the incident.
   Afghan government forces have been firing Scuds almost daily for
the past month at the Afghan guerrillas besieging Jalalabad, 45
miles from the Pakistan border. The Pakistan-based guerrillas
launched their offensive on the city 75 miles east of Kabul in
March after a Soviet troop withdrawal was completed in February.
   Soviet forces intervened in Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up the
Marxist government. The withdrawal was completed Feb. 15 under a
U.N.-brokered agreement.
   Najib and his Soviet-backed Marxist government have long accused
Pakistan of participating in the Afghan civil war by backing the
guerrillas, who also are supported by the United States, Saudi
Arabia and China. But the accusations against Pakistan have
intensified as the Jalalabad battle continues.
   Pakistan denies the charges.
   Amani said Pakistani forces, Arab advisers and the guerrillas on
Saturday launched the attack on Khost, 18 miles from the Pakistan
border, and the fighting continued Sunday.
   He said he had no casualty reports, but he claimed the attack
was led by two Pakistani military officers disguised as Afghans.
   He also claimed the opposition fired shells, rockets and mortars
at Ghazni, 80 miles from the Pakistani border in the past 24 hours,
killing nine civilians and two government soldiers. He said the
government returned fire, killing nine opposition fighters.
   At a checkpoint on the highway east of Kabul, civilians said
Sunday that about two buses were still arriving daily from Sarobi,
but no trucks. They said no traffic from Jalalabad was reaching the
capital.
</TEXT>
