<FIRST>u i AM-SovietSubmarine 3rdLd-Writethru a0674 04-09 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Submarine, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0674,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say 42 Sailors Died, Sub Carried Torpedoes with Nuclear Warheads</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OSL1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 4th pvs, `It said...,' to UPDATE with U.S.
comment. Pick up 5th pvs, `The vessel...' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Sunday that 42 sailors were
killed when a nuclear-powered submarine caught fire and exploded in
the Norwegian Sea, and it disclosed that two torpedoes on board
were armed with nuclear warheads.
   The official Tass news agency said the design of the warheads
``completely rules out'' the threat of radiation when the torpedoes
are under great pressure deep in the water.
   ``To ensure radiation safety, the nuclear-powered engine was
stopped and the power unit was effectively'' turned off, the agency
said.
   It said the submarine carried 69 men and that only 27 of them
survived.
   In Washington, Pentagon spokeswoman Maj. Kathy Wood said Sunday
the department had no comment on the Tass statement. President
Bush's national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, said U.S.
officials had no early indication of a radiation problem.
   ``The indications that we have received from the Soviet Union
are, there is none,'' Scowcroft said said on NBC-TV's ``Meet the
Press.''
   The vessel went down in international waters 120 miles southwest
of Norway's Bear Island and about 310 miles west of Tromsoe, on
Norway's northern coast. It was the third serious accident in the
Soviet nuclear fleet in 2{ years.
   Norwegian scientists were gathering deep-water samples Sunday,
and they placed equipment near the sunken ship that would monitor
radiation levels for years. Officials reported the vessel released
no radiation when it caught fire and exploded.
   Tass, in a dispatch from the Soviet Northern Fleet headquarters
in Murmansk, an arctic port, said:
   ``The crew of the torpedo-carrying nuclear-powered submarine was
made up of 69 men. Twenty-seven of them were saved. The crew of the
submarine displayed courage in the struggle for keeping it afloat.''
   Soviet officials said the survivors were rescued by a Soviet
warship and were bound for Murmansk.
   ``The submarine had on board two torpedoes with nuclear
warheads,'' Tass said.
   The torpedoes are designed to prevent radiation leaks even when
deeply submerged, the news agency said. In addition, it said, the
nuclear reactor was shut off and ``deadened'' during the accident
to prevent radioactive contamination of the environment.
   Tass did not identify the nuclear weapons on the sub, which sank
to a depth of more than 4,500 feet.
   The vessel, one of the Soviets' most advanced, was capable of
carrying more than a dozen long-range missiles in addition to the
torpedoes, U.S. officials have said.
   The sub, under the command of Capt. E. Vanin, was on its way
home from a long voyage when fire broke out in a compartment, the
military newspaper Red Star reported Sunday.
   ``The crew bravely fought the fire and tried to save the ship,''
the newspaper said, basing its information on an interview with
Captain P. Ishchenko of the Northern Fleet. ``The fight for life
continued for more than five hours, but with no results.''
   The decision was then made to abandon ship.
   The Soviets officially informed Norway of the accident nearly
nine hours after the vessel went down. The Norwegian news agency
NTB claimed Norwegian rescue helicopters could have reached the
ship several hours before Soviet fishing vessels if the Soviets had
promptly asked for help.
   Soviet officials were criticized for not providing accurate or
timely information after the 1986 explosion and fire at the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant. That incident sent a cloud of
radiation into the atmosphere that contaminated crops and livestock
in Europe.
   In Oslo, Defense Ministry spokesman Erik Senstad told a news
conference the Soviets declined an offer of Sea King helicopters
from a Norwegian rescue base 370 miles away, but he refused to say
if more lives could have been saved had they accepted the offer.
   Friday's sinking came five months after a reported near-meltdown
in a nuclear reactor aboard a Soviet icebreaker in Murmansk.
According to the newspaper Vodny Transport, a reactor operator
drained vital cooling water from an operating reactor rather than
one that was shut down for repairs.
   Had the water drained 30 minutes longer, a meltdown releasing
radiation into the air over the city of 440,000 would have
occurred, the newspaper said. The ``situation was liquidated'' in
four minutes, the newspaper said.
   In October 1986, three sailors died in a fire and explosion
aboard a Yankee-class nuclear-powered submarine in the Atlantic
Ocean that was armed with ballistic missiles.
</TEXT>
