<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Demonstration     04-09 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Demonstration,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Link Hands Against Nuclear Reprocessing Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of demonstrators linked hands Sunday in
an attempt to form a human chain around a northern Japan site where
the government is constructing a plant to reprocess spent nuclear
fuel.
   The protesters joined hands twice for three minutes, but police
said they did not cover the entire eight-mile distance around the
site near Rokkasho village, 320 miles northwest of Tokyo.
   Organizers said about 11,400 people, mostly housewives,
participated. Police put the number at closer to 7,500.
   There were no reports of violence or arrests, police said.
   In addition to reprocessing spent nuclear fuel, the plant is to
serve as an underground storage site for radioactive waste. It is
scheduled to start operation in 1991.
   Critics contend that unfavorable sea, weather and geographic
conditions at the Pacific coast site mean the plant would endanger
nearby communities.
   They also point to its proximity to the U.S. Misawa Air Base.
Last month, a U.S. Air Force plane accidentally dropped a dummy
bomb near a neighboring residential area during a practice exercise.
   ``The nuclear plant will hang over our lives and our
children's,'' said Hiroko Chiba.
   Japan, seeking to reduce its dependence on imported oil, plans
to rely more heavily on nuclear power. Officials have said that by
1995 nuclear plants will provide 36 percent of the country's
energy, up from the current 28 percent.
</TEXT>
