<FIRST>d i AM-BRF--CanadaQuake     04-09 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Canada Quake,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Hits British Columbia Interior</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALMON ARM, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interior of British
Columbia was jolted early Sunday morning by a mild earthquake.
There were no injuries or damage reported.
   The quake registered only 3.5 on the Richter scale, but shook
people awake when it struck.
   ``The Tremor was strong enough to be noticed but not strong
enough to be of concern,'' said Bob Horner of the Pacific
Geoscience Center. ``This is just one of the normal kinds of events
we see in this area from time to time.
   Salmon Arm, where the quake was centered, is about 200 miles
northeast of Vancouver, and about 100 miles north of the
U.S.-Canada border.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 can cause slight damage in a local area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
