<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Militants Surrender To Police and Army Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Sunday that 96
Sinhalese militants surrendered to police and army troops
apparently in response to President Ranasinghe Premadasa's amnesty
offer.
   Eighty-three militants gave themselves up in north-central
Anuradhapur and Kurunegala, and 13 others surrendered in southern
Moneragala, Galle and Matar, the government said in a statement.
   ``Many others have made contact with security forces wanting to
surrender,'' the statement said.
   Earlier this month, Premadasa announced the amnesty as part of a
peace plan under which Sinhalese and Tamil militants would receive
parliamentary seats and jobs in return for renouncing violence.
   Tamil rebels, fighting a six-year war for an independent
homeland, have not responded to the offer, the government said.
   Tamils, who are predominantly Hindu, comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. They allege discrimination by the mainly
Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population and
control the government and military.
   Sinhalese militants stepped up their attacks after the
government signed an India-sponsored peace accord in June 1987. The
pact was aimed at ending the Tamil struggle for self-rule in
northern and northeastern provinces.
   Sinhalese rebels say the 50,000 Indian soldiers in Sri Lanka,
deployed to help the government disarm Tamil rebels, compromise the
country's independence.
   India sponsored the accord because its own 60 million Tamils are
sympathetic to the rebel cause.
   But Sri Lanka's dominant Tamil rebel group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, has rejected the accord, saying it does not
meet enough Tamil demands for self-rule.
   The Tamil rebellion and the Sinhalese backlash have claimed at
least 12,500 lives.
</TEXT>
