<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-AirForce     04-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Air Force,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Upgraded Phantom Jet Fighter Presented to Air Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The air force received its first upgraded
Phantom jet fighter on Sunday, and officials said the improvements
will keep the nearly 35-year-old planes flying into the next
century.
   Air force commander Maj. Gen. Avihu Bin-Nun said the revamped
jet, called the Phantom 2000, will be used as a bomber and will be
able to compete with Soviet-made fighters used by the air forces of
many Arab states.
   ``The main mission of the plane will be air-to-ground
capabilities,'' Nun said on Israel radio. ``But it will be able to
deal with threats of the modern battlefield.''
   State-owned Israel Aircraft Industries plans to refurbish at
least 10 Phantom jets a year for the next five to six years at a
cost of less than $8 million a plane, said Yitzhak Geva, head of
the project.
   Israel has 150 Phantoms, according to the Jaffee Center for
Strategic Studies, a think tank in Tel Aviv.
   The U.S.-built F-4 Phantoms are being refitted with advanced
electronic and radar systems that originally were developed for the
Israeli Lavi fighter plane.
   The controversial Lavi project was canceled in 1987 because of
its high cost _ about $40 million per jet fighter.
   Israel received its first Phantoms in the early 1970s. The
director general of Israel Aircraft, Moshe Keret, said the revamped
jet will ``be able to take us well beyond the year 2000.''
