<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionClinics-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0706 04-09 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Clinics-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Hits Two Florida Clinics As Pro-Rights Activist Gather In Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs with additional comment from
clinic president; SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Ms. Struthers...,' to UPDATE number
at rally; SUBS 16th graf pvs to CORRECT to Marion County, sted Martin County.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Rally, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arsonists torched one Florida women's clinic and
may have been responsible for a fire at another early Sunday on the
eve of a huge abortion-rights march in Washington, authorities said.
   Deborah Struthers, president of the All Woman's Health Center in
Ocala and the Fort Myers Woman's Health Center, said both places
were hit at about the same time. Fort Myers is on Florida's
southwest coast. Ocala lies about 150 miles to the north.
   ``I don't understand the mentality of someone who would do
something like this _ these are terrorists we're dealing with
here,'' Ms. Struthers said. ``But it doesn't matter what they do,
we are not going to stop providing these services.''
   The Ocala fire was the second in less than 10 days. Someone
tried to burn the clinic down early Mar. 31. Officials said
Sunday's blaze looked like the work of the same arsonist.
   Information was scarce on the Fort Myers fire, which was
reported about 3:30 a.m. Sgt. Ed Stone of the Lee County Sheriff's
Department said authorities were still looking into its cause
Sunday afternoon.
   About a half hour after firefighters got that call, a neighbor
spotted the flames in Ocala and called firefighters. According to
fire department spokesman Barry Britton, they responded quickly,
but the entire clinic already was burning.
   ``At this point you have the four exterior walls standing,'' he
said. ``The roof is burnt off it and the interior is totally
gutted.''
   A police spokesman said investigators have some leads.
   ``There are some possiblities, but nothing we can hang our hats
on,'' said Sgt. Ken Hall of the Ocala police department.
   Ms. Struthers said it was because she had anticipated trouble
that she stayed home from the Washington rally, at which hundreds
of thousands of abortion rights activists marched from the
Washington Monument to the Capitol.
   ``I just didn't prepare well enough,'' she added. ``It just
never dawned on us that someone would be that disturbed and
unstable and aggressive and vicious.''
   Ms. Struthers said she had no estimate of damage to the Fort
Myers clinic, but said it would not open Monday.
   ``It appears to be pretty well gutted out,'' Stone said.
   In addition to local authorities, agents of the state fire
marshal's office are working on both fires. The federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms was also called in, Britton said.
   Stone said that agency would probably look into the Fort Myers
incident as well.
   Ocala anti-abortion activists say they're not responsible for
the fires.
   ``People in my group had speculated (about) the possibility of
the abortionists doing it themselves,'' said Ed Martin, president
of Marion County Right to Life.
   He said they would have done it to draw attention to their cause
and damage the anti-abortion movement.
   ``The only way that this can be calmed down is for something
like this to happen where a clinic goes up and it puts a bad light
on our movement,'' he said.
   Ms. Struthers said that's ``absurd.''
   ``In Ocala, the anti-choice people have been very vocal and
quite aggressive in their actions,'' she said. ``I wouldn't say
that those are the people responsible. I wouldn't like to point
fingers but we have had some of the most aggressive picketing in
the state.''
   She said the violent tactics wouldn't keep her organziation from
its work.
   ``What these people don't realize is that it reaffirms our
commitment to this. It doesn't make us think `This is too much
trouble and we'll just go away.' It makes us stronger.''
</TEXT>
