<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0686 04-09 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede SIDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Israelis Destroy Dinghy Carrying Palestinians Headed For Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Israel now saying two guerrillas
were aboard dinghy; Palestinian faction says there were four, not announced
if guerrillas were killed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli naval patrol off the coast of
Lebanon opened fire Sunday on a rubber dinghy carrying two
Palestinian guerrillas toward Israel and destroyed the vessel, the
navy commander announced.
   In Sidon, Lebanon, a Libyan-sponsored Palestinian faction also
reported the encounter but said there were four guerrillas aboard
the dinghy, including one woman. It made no mention of casualties.
   Maj. Gen. Micha Ram, the navy chief, said the Israeli boat Dvora
was on routine patrol when the dinghy was seen just north of the
Israeli border town Rosh Haniqra.
   Israel television interviewed the commander of the Dvora but did
not identify him by name.
   ``I spotted ... a rubber dinghy with two people and I was
certain of two things,'' the commander said in the television
interview. ``It was headed for the border and the men inside were
wearing green uniforms.''
   ``It was clear they were terrorists,'' he said, adding that he
could not identify them further.
   The commander said his boat fired flares and pursued the dinghy
for a short time before approaching and shooting. ``We opened fire
and in a matter of seconds the boat sank,'' he said.
   Ram said the patrol boat did not stay in the area to search for
survivors so ``as not to endanger the Dvora.'' The military said
Israeli forces suffered no casualties.
   The Palestine Popular Struggle Front said in a statement issued
in the southern port city of Sidon that the dinghy was intercepted
off Ras el-Bayyada, six miles north of the Israeli border.
   It said four guerrillas ``were on their way to our Palestinian
coast in a rubber dinghy.
   ``Our guerrillas fired rockets at the Israeli enemy boats. The
enemy used all kinds of weapons in the clash and dropped flares
that lit the whole area,'' the statement said. It did not elaborate
and a second statement said only that one of the guerrillas was a
woman.
   The Popular Struggle Front is based in Syria and is opposed to
Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat's recent
conciliatory moves toward Israel.
   Washington has expressed concern over recent infiltration
attempts by guerrillas from Lebanon. Arafat and his aides have said
the PLO's renunciation of terrorism does not mean a halt to
guerrilla operations against Israeli military targets.
   Also Sunday, an Israeli soldier suffered light wounds when an
armored personnel carrier hit a land mine in southern Lebanon, the
Israeli military command said.
   The incident occurred in Israel's self-declared security zone in
Lebanon.
   Israel carved out the zone in 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of
its troops from Lebanon, ending a three-year occupation of the
southern part of the country.
</TEXT>
