<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-TerryThomas     04-09 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Terry Thomas,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ailing British Comedian Feted At Gala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British comedian Terry-Thomas, who has appeared in
more 40 films, was honored Sunday night at a charity gala to raise
money for treatment of the Parkinson's disease he suffers from.
   ``Never in my history in show business has there been anything
as big as this,'' said Jack Douglas, the British actor who
organized the sold-out event with journalist Richard Hope-Hawkins.
   Terry-Thomas, 77, has suffered from the degenerative muscle
disease for a decade and was too ill to attend.
   The comedian with the famous gap-toothed smile was represented
by his two children, Tiger and Cushan, Douglas said in an interview.
   The five-hour show at the 2,652-seat Theater Royal featured
performances by singers Phil Collins and Eartha Kitt, among others.
The audience also heard tape-recorded tributes to Terry-Thomas from
celebrities in Los Angeles including Dudley Moore, Mickey Rooney
and Lynn Redgrave.
   Douglas said the show raised about $106,000. He said that about
$50,000 will go into a trust for Terry-Thomas, the stage name of
the actor born Thomas Terry Hoar Stevens.
   The rest of the proceeds will be divided between the
London-based Parkinson's Disease Society and the Entertainment
Artist's Benevolent Fund, Douglas said.
   He said the show was videotaped so Terry-Thomas and his wife,
Belinda, could watch it later this week at their home in Barnes,
southwest London.
   Douglas described himself as an admirer and a fan of
Terry-Thomas, whom he first saw in a 1946 London stage variety show.
   Terry-Thomas' films include ``I'm All Right, Jack,'' ``It's A
Mad Mad Mad Mad World'' and ``Those Magnificent Men In Their Flying
Machines.''
   Douglas and Terry-Thomas appeared together in the 1959 film
``Carlton-Browne of the F.O.,'' known in the United States as ``Man
In A Cocked Hat.''
   But Douglas he said he only got to know Terry-Thomas when he
started to organize the gala three months ago.
   ``When I looked at Terry in his very bare apartment, his food
paid for by the Entertainment Artist's Benevolent Fund, I thought,
`There but for the grace of God go any of us,''' Douglas said.
   Douglas acknowledged that the high cost of specialized health
care could quickly eat away the money raised by the benefit, even
though Britain's system of socialized medicine keeps costs somewhat
in check.
   ``If this isn't (enough money), we'll do another show next
year,'' Douglas said.
</TEXT>
