<HEAD>Former Paraguayan Dictator Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Paraguayan dictator Alfredo
Strossner was hospitalized Sunday with congestive heart failure, a
doctor said.
   A doctor at the Heart Institute said Stroessner has had a mild
form of congestive heart failure for many years and the condition
was not severe. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 76-year-old Stroessner was ousted in a violent coup Feb. 5
and since has been living in exile in Guaratuba, an Atlantic resort
about 260 miles east of Sao Paulo.
   The doctor said Stroessner underwent several tests Sunday and
will undergo more on Monday.
   Paraguay's foreign minister, Luis Maria Argana, said last week
that his government, acting for ``humanitarian reasons,'' was
looking for a country with advanced medical facilities to treat
Stroessner's prostate cancer.
   He said the United States had refused to grant Stroessner a
temporary visa to receive treatment.
