<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Rockets 1stLd-Writethru   04-09 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Rockets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0730,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Search Company In Technology-Export Probe</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD that BBC television report on case
to air Monday, EDITS throughout. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors searched the offices of
a West German company in an investigation into exports of rocket
technology to Iraq, a news magazine reported Sunday.
   The Hamburg-based Stern magazine said prosecutors on Friday
seized documents during a search of the MBB-Transtechnica company
offices in Munich. The company is a subsidiary of the aerospace and
armament giant Messerschmidt-Boelkow-Blohm, according to the
magazine.
   A British television report to be aired Monday makes similar
claims, according to a news release issued by the British Broadcast
Corp. The report will be shown on ``Panorama,'' the BBC's most
respected current affairs show.
   Stern said in a statement that its report will appear in the
magazine's Thursday edition.
   It said Friday's search was related to an investigation into
another West German company, Gildemeister Projecta. The magazine
said that company was the general contractor for a ``secret rocket
development laboratory in Iraq disguised as a civilian university
institute.''
   Stern said Gildemeister's offices in Bielefeld were searched
three weeks ago.
   The searches apparently were linked to a government announcement
that it would tighten export regulations, which came under attack
by U.S. authorities earlier this year. U.S. officials accused Libya
of building a chemical weapons factory and said West German firms
were involved in the construction.
   The prosecutor's office in Munich was closed on Sunday and
officials could not be reached for comment.
   In several recent reports Stern said West German companies were
involved in exporting technology used in the development of a
Condor 2 rocket, with the capability of carrying a nuclear warhead.
Stern said the rocket has a 620-mile range.
   According to the magazine, MBB-Transtechnica pulled out of
weapons development projects in Egypt and Argentina following
pressure from the West German and U.S. governments. But it said MBB
continues to deliver technology to Iraq.
   Last week the firm delivered equipment to Iraq that can be used
to measure missile trajectories, Stern said. It quoted company
officials as saying all deliveries were legal and received the
required government export permits.
   Stern said the federal Economics Ministry withdrew previously
approved export permits for Gildemeister on grounds that federal
officials were not told the real nature of the project in Iraq.
   The magazine said it also had documents that showed Gildemeister
had exported electronic components, developed by a U.S. company,
for the Iraqi project.
</TEXT>
