<FIRST>r a AM-Drive-byShootings     04-09 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drive-by Shootings,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighborhood Rallies Against Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred residents of a drug-torn
neighborhood marched through the streets Sunday in an anti-crack
protest fueled by weekend shootings that left two dead and 10
injured in another part of the city.
   ``We are going to march and shout and sing and pray till this
crack cocaine is completely eradicated from our community,'' said
the Rev. Cecil Williams, who led the march through the Ocean View
neighborhood.
   Although the march and rally had been planned for several weeks,
a drive-by ambush and another shooting less than two miles away in
the Bayview-Hunters Point district gave people another reason to
participate, Williams said.
   ``People are being killed, being openly killed,'' said Williams,
pastor of Glide Memorial United Methodist Church.
   Community and religious leaders in Bayview-Hunters Point had
urged their own residents to march in protest of the shootings in
the neighborhood hard hit by gang violence.
   ``It's getting to be summertime, it's hot, and if we don't look
at this problem aggressively, we're going to have a long, hot
summer,'' warned Joseph Landry, chairman of the Bayview-Hunters
Point Crime Abatement Committee.
   The neighborhood was the scene early Saturday of the worst mass
shooting in San Francisco since five people were killed and 11
wounded in the 1975 Golden Dragon Massace in Chinatown.
   Two people were killed and nine injured in the automatic weapon
ambush, which police said may have been a case of mistaken
identity. One remained in serious condition Sunday at Mission
Emergency Hospital.
   In a second incident Saturday night, two men were abducted by
four others carrying an Uzi machine gun and a .45-caliber handgun.
One of the abducted men was shot. He was in stable condition Sunday
at Mission Emergency.
   ``This type of action is not uncommon for gangs,'' said police
officer Jerry Langford.
   Police have beefed up patrols in the neighborhood and asked for
anyone with information about the shootings to come forward, but
residents were uneasy.
   ``It's unreal,'' said JoAnne Miller, a member of the San
Francisco School board and a neighbor and acquaintance of one of
the slain. ``Everybody's scared now. It was never like this.''
</TEXT>
