<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PatientSuicides     04-09 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Patient Suicides,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Suicides Prompt Review at Mental Health Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national accreditation group has begun an
investigation into the suicides of nine patients in 18 months at
the Milwaukee County Mental Health Complex, officials say.
   The deaths occurred between May 1987 and last October, raising
questions about the level of care at the facility. However, the
center's acting administrator, Jon E. Gudeman, insisted that his
staff wasn't responsible for the deaths.
   After the situation was reported by an advocacy group for the
mentally ill, the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare
Organizations in Chicago requested records on the suicides and
asked what corrective steps had been taken.
   The deaths included four patients who hanged themselves, one who
suffocated with a plastic bag, one who took an overdose of
anti-depressant, one who jumped through a window to his death, one
who killed himself by carbon monoxide poisoning and one who drowned
in Lake Michigan.
   Gudeman said he provided the information but hasn't received a
reply. He told an interviewer last week that hospitalization
reduces the risk of suicide but ``doesn't totally eliminate it.''
   He said a 1980 study of six mental hospitals in New York City
estimated there were 1.3 to 2.5 inpatient suicides for every 1,000
patients. Even in 1987 and 1988, the Milwaukee figures were within
that range, he said.
   ``In my belief, they received good and proper care,'' Gudeman
said of the suicide victims.
   However, Thomas E. Dixon, an attorney for the Wisconsin
Coalition for Advocacy in Madison, called the number of suicides
among the patients at the complex ``an outrage.''
   ``Something is missing,'' he said. ``It may be the level of
staffing, the training of the staff, the supervision of the
patients. Something is missing, though we don't have any way of
knowing exactly what it is.''
   Gudeman said he has made policy changes in response to the
suicides. Some were prompted by an inspection by the state Division
of Health that found five deficiencies in the care of a 20-year-old
man who suffocated himself with a plastic trash can liner.
   ``This man was talking about killing himself and how he was
going to do it, and he was not put on suicidal precautions,'' said
Vicki Lauridsen, a state investigator. ``And that to us was rather
negligent.
   ``The staff did not respond in a normal fashion,'' she said.
``They did not take this person seriously. They goofed.''
   Gudeman said changes at the complex include more one-on-one
observations of patients by a staff member, in-service training on
care of suicidal patients and increased clinical reviews of patient
charts.
</TEXT>
