<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-PanAm     04-09 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Pan Am,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Probe Claims of Lax Security at Pan Am</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Transport Secretary Paul Channon on Sunday
ordered an urgent inquiry into a newspaper's claim of security
lapses on Pan Am airliners at London's Heathrow airport, his office
said.
   ``The Secretary has ordered an inquiry. He has asked for an
urgent report from Pan Am on the matter,'' said a department
spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Monday's editions of The Sun tabloid carried an account by a
reporter who said he worked undercover for two weeks in a baggage
handling job at Pan Am and noted repeated security breaches.
   The reporter, George Pascoe-Watson, applied for the job using
the fictitious name George Watson two weeks after 270 people died
in the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Soctland.
   He was hired three months later even though he lied about
previous jobs and gave the names of two friends as sponsors, he
said.
   Pascoe-Watson said that on one occasion more than 50 pieces of
luggage for Flight 103 to New York passed through an X-ray scanner,
but the Pan Am security guard glanced at the video screen only
seven times.
   He also said he was allowed to wander unsupervised through
restricted areas at Heathrow despite security rules that new staff
must be escorted.
   ``Just hours after starting work on my first day I was left
unsupervised and unchecked to pack the Israeli soccer team's
luggage on to a Qantas 747 bound for Melbourne,'' Pascoe-Watson
said.
   Pan Am denied the charge that the reporter was unsupervised.
   Peter Joel, the airline's spokesman in London, said: ``We
believe it is premature for the Department of Transport to accept
that a breach of security has occurred based solely on the
allegations of The Sun and before investigations are completed.''
   A Heathrow airport official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said: ``At no time did Mr. Pascoe-Watson constitute a security risk
and his temporary pass allowing access under escort was issued in
the proper manner.''
   After the Lockerbie crash, reporters from three British
newspapers described how they were allowed to wander through the
airport and board airliners unchallenged.
   British and U.S. authorities have been criticized for not
issuing public warnings after they received anonymous threats
against Pan Am airliners before the bombing occurred.
</TEXT>
