<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Law     04-09 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Law,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders Vow to Oppose Equal Rights Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's justice minister on Sunday proposed
action on a civil rights law that is denounced by religious leaders
who say it does not recognize the special nature of Judaism in the
state.
   The proposed ``Basic Law on Human Rights'' was first introduced
in 1965.
   It calls for equality ``between men and women and all people
regardless of religion, nationality, race, or ethnicity.'' It would
not apply in the occupied West Bank or Gaza Strip, captured from
Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war, which are ruled through military
and not civil law.
   Justice Minister Dan Meridor said he was concerned that civil
liberties had been put aside in the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``When a nation is struggling, people start to think what does
it matter what an individual says, or what peoples' rights are,''
Meridor told Israel radio. ``I think the time has come to set
matters straight.''
   Israel has no constitution and the Supreme Court cannot declare
parliamentary legislation illegal. Civil rights come from a mixture
of parliamentary laws and Supreme Court decisions.
   But if approved, the proposed measure gives the Supreme Court
authority to reject laws that violate civil rights. Meridor said
Jewish religious courts would retain their exclusive authority to
conduct marriages and divorces.
   The bill was accepted by the Cabinet and referred to a special
committee.
   At Sunday's Cabinet meeting Minister of Religious Affairs Avner
Shaki vowed to oppose the bill.
   ``I told Meridor that the state is first a Jewish state and then
a democratic and humanitarian state,'' he said. ``After all Judaism
includes these concepts.''
   In a debate on television, Shaki said he will not accept the
bill unless it states that man was ``created by God in his image''
and that Israel is a Jewish state.
   ``We will never agree to this,'' said Shulamit Aloni, leader of
the liberal Citizens Rights Movement. ``It's like calling South
Africa a white state.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
