<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writehtru   04-09 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writehtru,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei close comments.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen Monday
morning, while stock prices dropped sharply after early morning
gains on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 132.78 yen, and moved in a range of
132.52-132.78. It stood at 132.67, up 0.59 yen from last Friday's
close of 132.08 yen at mid-morning.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 189.27-point
gainer last Friday, lost 266.74 points, or 0.81 percent, to finish
the morning trading at 32,918.31.
   Currency dealers said they expect no major shifts Monday because
of players' caution about possible intervention by central banks.
   The dollar's higher opening compared to its finish at 132.75 yen
in New York last Friday. The Tokyo market customarily follows the
trend of the New York market in the absence of major
market-affecting news.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index opened firm, reflecting
stable exchange rates and the strong showings of the New York and
other stock markets last week.
   The main index, however, declined sharply in late morning
trading because of market anxiety about an unstable domestic
political situation.
   It was learned last week that Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
was closely linked to the controversial firm at the center of a
major bribery scandal. Members of his own party have called for his
resignation.
   Prosecutors are reportedly preparing to question high-ranking
politicians linked to the affair.
