<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Milken-Support Bjt   04-09 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken-Support, Bjt,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milken Friends Pledge Campaign Against Charges; Drexel Shows Sympathy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and colleagues of Michael Milken are
pledging to mount a public campaign against government charges that
the deposed Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. junk-bond mogul is a
criminal.
   Dozens of supporters _ many of whom refused to identify
themselves or even say whether they worked for Drexel _ attended
Milken's arraignment Friday in U.S. District Court on 98 counts of
racketeering and securities fraud.
   Another 90 corporate executives recently paid for a full-page ad
in The New York Times and the Wall Street Journal supporting
Milken. Its slogan, ``Mike Milken, We Believe in You,'' has been
emblazoned on baseball caps and T-shirts.
   ``We're going to turn this around,'' said Martin Klein, a New
York bankruptcy attorney and friend of Milken's, who attended the
hearing at which Milken pleaded innocent. ``It's manifestly unfair.
It'll be a test of the government's tactics.''
   Milken, 42, is widely credited with reshaping corporate America
in the 1980s from his Beverly Hills, Calif., office through the
sale of high-yield junk bonds that allowed small- and medium-sized
companies to expand rapidly or take over much larger firms.
   His work helped catapult Drexel from a third-tier investment
house into the fifth-largest firm of its kind in the United States
since he moved the junk bond division to the West Coast in the
mid-1970s.
   He also is praised by clients and friends as a man concerned
with Third World debt and educational issues who donates to charity
much of his annual pay, which was in the hundreds of millions of
dollars.
   ``Mike has always performed according to the highest standards
of professionalism, honesty, integrity and ethical conduct,'' said
the pro-Milken ad.
   The ad was signed by presidents and chief executives from firms
including MCI Corp., Metromedia Co. and GAF Corp. Many of those
same names have been passed on to reporters by a public relations
firm Milken hired to speak for him.
   Milken has been a target of government prosecutors for more than
two years and was indicted March 29 for a series of alleged schemes
that purportedly defrauded clients, investors and the public by
violating securities laws.
   Supporters and defense lawyers claim Milken has been unfairly
persecuted in the government's crackdown on white-collar crime in
an attempt to nail the highest paid and one of the most prominent
figures on Wall Street.
   ``I think there's been enough publicity about the government
being so heavy-handed and the provenance of the leaks being so
clear that the view is it's high time this man had his day in
court,'' said Ralph Ingersoll II, chairman of Ingersoll
Publications Co. and a close friend of Milken's.
   Defense lawyers also charged that the government in its
indictment released Milken's earnings _ more than $1 billion in
four years _ to sully public opinion against Milken.
   ``It's a question on the minds of thousands of people, including
people who will be jurors in this case,'' said Milken attorney
Arthur L. Liman.
   The government reportedly has been upset by Drexel's statements
of support for Milken, whom prosecutors allege masterminded the six
felonies Drexel has agreed to plead guilty to in its record $650
million securities fraud settlement.
   After Milken's indictment, Drexel decried government ``leaks and
innuendos'' against him. Drexel said he was responsible for opening
``new capital markets to hundreds of companies and helping to
create hundreds of thousands of jobs.''
   And after Friday's arraignment, at which Milken was released
without bail pending the setting of a bond, Drexel distanced itself
from direct support for Milken but didn't oppose cheerleading by
others.
   ``Some individuals have chosen to express their support for Mike
at this very difficult and emotional time for him,'' a statement
said. `We understand their desire to express their feelings.''
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder and Assistant U.S. Attorney
Bruce Baird denied reports that the government asked Drexel to bar
employees from staging a courthouse rally for Milken. Supporters
did gather in Beverly Hills, where Drexel was holding its annual
junk bond conference sans Milken.
   None of those attending the arraignment or cheering Milken as he
exited the courthouse afterward would say whether they worked for
Drexel.
   Despite Drexel's earlier support for Milken, it is expected by
prosecutors to state Milken caused the crimes cited in its plea
bargain, which has not yet taken effect.
   In addition, Drexel also has agreed to cooperate with the
government, and that might require the firm to provide evidence
against Milken. A separate settlement of civil charges against
Drexel reportedly bars Drexel employees from ever talking business
with Milken.
</TEXT>
