<DOCNO> AP890409-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WirelessCable Bjt   04-09 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wireless Cable, Bjt,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Hopes To Make Dent In Cable TV Market With ``Wireless'' Cable
TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE ZGANJAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALTA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greg Oswald figures he's got the answer when
it comes to breaking into the close-knit cable television industry:
take an old technology, but apply it in a new way.
   His company, Capital Wireless, has just begun broadcasting cable
programs to customers via a local transmitter in the Helderberg
Mountains, just southwest of Albany.
   The signals are transmitted through the air _ the way
conventional television and radio stations are _ avoiding the high
expense and regulatory restrictions of cable installation.
   Oswald believes his company will be able to make inroads in a
local market already littered with nine cable TV companies and give
an industry that's seen little competition a run for its money.
   ``It'll be hard to break in here,'' Oswald said. ``But if I can
make it here, I can make it anywhere.''
   Capital Wireless is one of only about dozen wireless cable
companies operating in the United States. The firm is headquartered
in Malta, about 30 miles from its satellite receiver in the
Helderbergs. Its signal can reach as far as 60 miles away.
   The company's receiver, or dish, takes in signals from more than
30 other satellites and transmits them to Capital Wireless
customers. An antenna placed on each customer's house collects the
signal, and converters near the antenna and on the television set
convert the signal so it can be received on the TV.
   ``Wireless is the purest form of transmission because it's
through the air,'' said Oswald, president of Capital Wireless.
   This means customers don't have to worry about service being
interrupted by downed cable lines. But it does mean that mountains,
tall buildings and even heavy foliage can block the signal. Experts
say that's a significant defect because it limits the product's
availability.
   Capital Wireless offers 21 channels _ including local stations,
superstations like WWOR in New York City and satellite networks
such as CNN and MTV _ along with a premium movie channel and the
Disney Channel.
   Oswald says the company has the potential to double the number
of channels it offers using a method developed by General Electric
Co. The method involves splitting each channel into two.
   Capital Wireless charges $13.50 a month for its basic service.
Premium channels cost an additional $10 a month.
   The average cost of basic cable service nationwide is $14.60 a
month and the average subscriber gets at least 35 channels,
according to John Wolf, director of the National Cable Television
Association in Washington.
   About 55 percent of people nationwide subscribe to cable
television, said William Finneran, chairman of the New York State
Commission on Cable TV. In New York state, that figure climbs to 61
percent, he said.
   ``Those are hard numbers to compete with,'' Finneran said. ``I
know of no success stories where wireless has appreciably captured
even a corner of a market where cable exists. But that's not to say
it can't happen.''
   Oswald is banking on that. And he thinks his ace in the hole is
a strong emphasis on customer service.
   ``You're not too conscientious when you're the only guy in
town,'' he said, referring to local cable operators. ``Sometimes
people get that feeling pretty quickly.''
   Oswald said his company, which began offering its service in
March, signed 50 customers and received 3,000 inquiries in its
first week. He estimates the firm will have 10,000 customers in 18
months.
   Oswald believes many of his new customers were cable subscribers
who jumped ship because of unresponsive cable operators.
   Cable operators realize this is an area they have neglected,
said officials with the Cable TV Association of New York.
   ``It's part of the growing pain we went through,'' said Richard
Alteri, the association's president. ``We have been going through
various stages. The stage we're at now is one where we are devoting
our energies toward increased customer service.''
   Whatever the outcome of the battle for cable subscribers,
customers likely will reap the rewards of competition: improved
products and service and competitive prices, Oswald said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
